nor from the United States to articulate a global Indigeneity, Keaney foregrounds the entwinement of reproduction, race, and affect. By focusing on queer family making, Keaney demonstrates how reproduction fosters a queer multiracial imaginary of kinship.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aChildren of gay parents. 0aGay-parent families. 0aHuman reproductive technologyxSocial aspects. 0aRace awareness. 0aRace relations. 0aSexual minorities' families. 0aSperm donors. 0aSurrogate motherhood. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / American / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311099775040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781478027492?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781478027492423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781478027492/original  a978-3-11-099775-0  Duke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles